				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">1) Go team Xilinx (they are the leader/Cypress or Microchip of FPGA, where Altera is like Atmel)
<br />2) Get the smallest FPGA that can fit all the projects you're thinking of. Smaller FPGA = significantly less routing/fitting time.
<br />
<br />3) Get a development board with an integrated USB microcontroller. USB JTAG are very expensive and unnecessary! Having an option for power over USB is also very convenient.
<br />4) Get a board with common IDC headers so you can build your own peripherals, it sucks having to buy $25 obscure connectors
<br />5) Get a board with voltage/current protection on I/Os
<br />6) Get a board with full schematic published
<br />
<br />Your DE1 board satisfies at least 3-4 :P If you don't think you're going to be needing external RAM, I would really suggest the $59 (academic price) Basys2 from Digilent! It looks extremely small/portable and the 100K/250K (250K can fit a NES) gate FPGA will fit fast.
<br />
<br />I'd say don't get an introduction to logic through HDL book. Learn logic, then learn an HDL. You will be a more able hacker for it! I guess I would recommend a used copy of Floyd's Digital Fundamentals though I think I could condense an excellent Digital curriculum into &lt;100 pages. Hands on simulation of 7400 chips really helps! In an intro to digital class I used an ancient copy of Electronic Workbench, which totally sucked, then I got Logic Works, which still kinda sucks, but I can't find/write a better program...
<br />
<br />Also you probably really don't need to buy a Verilog book, if you're dedicated you'll soon outgrow it. I have a crapload of textbooks I'm stuck with that are not useful anymore as references. From now on I'm just Googling whatever I don't know. I learned the essentials of Verilog in a few days just following online tutorials, but after about 5 years of digital tinkering.</div>

